* 4. When does it schedule ?

    func main() {
        // crete goroutines
        for _, i := range imgs {
            go process(i)               -> goroutine creation
        }                                   run new goroutines, run from this
        ...
        // wait
        <-ch                            -> goroutine blocking
    }                                       pause ASAP
    func process(img) {
        // create another goroutine
        go createMetrics()

        complicatedAlgo(img)

        // write to file                
        f, err := os.OpenFile()         -> blocking syscalls, network I/O
        ...                                 blocks the thread too!
    }

* 5. What are the scheduler goals ?

1. use small number of kernel threads;
2. support high concurrency;
3. leverage parallelism, scale over N cores;

* 6. How does it work?

Schedules at operations that *should* or *would* affect *goroutine* *execution*.

The runtime causes a switch into the scheduler under-the-hood, and the scheduler may schedule *different* *goroutine* on *this* *thread*.

.image ./imgs/execution.png _ 400

* 7. How to multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

Break into:
1. When to create threads?
2. How to distribute across threads?

* 7. How to multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

Tracking run goroutines: runqueues

    joins goroutines that are ready-to-run and need to be scheduled,
    are allocated in FIFO runqueues.

.image ./imgs/execution_2.png _ 100
.image ./imgs/execution_3.png _ 200

* 7. How to multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

- assuming 2 cores:

    func main() { //g_main
        // crete goroutines
        for _, i := range imgs {
            go process(i)               -> creates g1, g2
        }
        ...
        // wait
        <-ch                            -> block goroutine
    }
    func process(img) {} //g1

* 7. How to NOT multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

1. All goroutines on a single thread
> Doesnt allow any concurrency;
> impossible to do parallelism;

.image ./imgs/execution_4.png

* 7. How to NOT multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

2. create and destroy threads per goroutine

> breaks the lightweight purpose of using goroutines

* 7. How to REALLY multiplex goroutines onto kernel threads?

I. create threads when you need them;
II. keep threads for reuse;
III. threads get goroutines from the runqueue;

