* 9. experimenting

- modified go scheduler

    global runqueue
    number of goroutine running threads = number of CPU cores

- everything else on runtime not modified

> test

    creates #Cores goroutines in parallel
    until the N total of goroutines are created

> machines

1. 4 core CPU
2. 16 core CPU

* 9. experimenting

1. 4-core: modified scheduler takes *4x* *longer*
2. 16-core:modified scheduler takes *31x* *longer*

.image ./imgs/t_main_scale_4.png _ 400

* 10. scaling the runqueue

- use N runqueues on N-core machine;
- a thread *claims* a runqueue to run goroutines;
- reuse threads.

* 10. scaling the runqueue

.image ./imgs/t_main_scale_5.png

Number of CPU cores (N) = number of runqueues = 2.

* 10. scaling the runqueue

Number of CPU cores (N) = number of runqueues = 2.

.image ./imgs/t_main_scale_5.png

- empty runqueue, get work from waiting runqueues;
- "steals" half of the other runqueue work;
- picked at random;

* 10. scaling the runqueue

.image ./imgs/t_main_steal_0.png

