* 11. handoff

- mechanism for runqueue transfering;
- acts on monitored blocked threads.

why cant the thread hand the runqueue?

    could give up the runqueue unnecessarily


* 11. handoff

- mechanism for runqueue transfering;
- unpark a thread or start if needed;

does not affect the limit:
- limit applies to *goroutine-running* threads only;
- original thread is blocked, another can take its place.

Effect:
- prevents goroutine starvation!

* 11. handoff

.image ./imgs/t_main_handoff_0.png

Number of CPU cores (N) = number of runqueues = 2.

* 11. handoff

.image ./imgs/t_main_handoff_1.png _ 700

Number of CPU cores (N) = number of runqueues = 2.

* 11. The scheduler

- scalability with # of cores;
- threads dont wait for work;
- work is *balanced* with "work-stealing";
- *handoff* prevents starvation from blocked threads;

* 11. The scheduler

- reuse threads;
- limits #(goroutine-running) threads to CPU cores (=GOMAXPROCS);
- uses distributed runqueues;

* 11. The scheduler

Scheduling points are *cooperative*, the program calls into the scheduler.

    // CPU bound, long running
    func complicatedAlgo(img) {
        // doenst create goroutines
        // doesnt block
        ...
    }

> This can starve the runqueue

* 12. Preemption

- scheduler implements asynchronous preemption;

> background thread "sysmon" - monitor;
> detects and unschedules long-running goroutines.
(> 10ms)

- go to global runqueue;
- lower priority source;

* 12. scheduler Goals

- uses small number of kernel threads;
- supports high concurrency;
- leverage parallelism to N cores;

* 12. limitations

- no goroutine priority: due to FIFO runqueues;
- no strong preemption: no strong fairness / latency guarantees;
- no localization.

